04040nam a22004935i 9780226532653DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226532653  a(DE-B1597)524171  a(OCoLC)592756276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a5012231 aMitchell, Sandra D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnsimple Truths :bScience, Complexity, and Policy /cSandra D. Mitchell. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Complexities of organization: How we think about the world -- t3. Complexities of evolved diversity: Laws -- t4. Science: How we investigate the world -- t5. Policy: How we act in the world -- t6. Integrative pluralism -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world is complex, but acknowledging its complexity requires an appreciation for the many roles context plays in shaping natural phenomena. In Unsimple Truths, Sandra Mitchell argues that the long-standing scientific and philosophical deference to reductive explanations founded on simple universal laws, linear causal models, and predict-and-act strategies fails to accommodate the kinds of knowledge that many contemporary sciences are providing about the world. She advocates, instead, for a new understanding that represents the rich, variegated, interdependent fabric of many levels and kinds of explanation that are integrated with one another to ground effective prediction and action. Mitchell draws from diverse fields including psychiatry, social insect biology, and studies of climate change to defend “integrative pluralism”—a theory of scientific practices that makes sense of how many natural and social sciences represent the multi-level, multi-component, dynamic structures they study. She explains how we must, in light of the now-acknowledged complexity and contingency of biological and social systems, revise how we conceptualize the world, how we investigate the world, and how we act in the world. Ultimately Unsimple Truths argues that the very idea of what should count as legitimate science itself should change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aComplexity (Philosophy). 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience, scientific, policy, politics, political, history, philosophy, historical, philosophical, complexity, universal laws, knowledge, understanding, interdependent, explanation, prediction, action, interdisciplinary, psychiatry, biology, climate change, integrative pluralism, theory, theoretical, practices, conceptualization, legitimacy, epistemology, organization, emergence, reduction, diversity, possibility, contingent, analysis, considerations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226532653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226532653/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles